issue.title: `computeProposerIndex` to return and propagate an error?
issue.body:
In spec v0.9.x, [`compute_proposer_index`](https://github.com/ethereum/eth2.0-specs/blob/v0.9.1/specs/core/0_beacon-chain.md#compute_proposer_index) asserts `indices > 0`, where previously this was unguarded and would result in a `ZeroDivisionError` (e.g. in [`get_beacon_proposer_index`](https://github.com/ethereum/eth2.0-specs/blob/v0.8.4/specs/core/0_beacon-chain.md#get_beacon_proposer_index)).

Now that this is explicitly checked in the python spec, should ZRNT return and propagate an error in order to maintain equivalence?

comment.body:
This is based on my understanding of the following error behavior/equivalence in the 2 specs:

error type | ZRNT | Pyspec
------|----------|-----
expected error/crash | Go error return | AssertionError or IndexError
serious crash, bug | Go panic | Other python exceptions

issue.title: `computeProposerIndex` to return and propagate an error?
issue.body:
In spec v0.9.x, [`compute_proposer_index`](https://github.com/ethereum/eth2.0-specs/blob/v0.9.1/specs/core/0_beacon-chain.md#compute_proposer_index) asserts `indices > 0`, where previously this was unguarded and would result in a `ZeroDivisionError` (e.g. in [`get_beacon_proposer_index`](https://github.com/ethereum/eth2.0-specs/blob/v0.8.4/specs/core/0_beacon-chain.md#get_beacon_proposer_index)).

Now that this is explicitly checked in the python spec, should ZRNT return and propagate an error in order to maintain equivalence?

This is based on my understanding that a ZRNT/golang error = expected crash, and panic = serious crash.
